@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

     @{u}Introduction@{uu}

The Robot Auto Racing Simulation (RARS) is a simulation of auto racing in
which the cars are driven by robots. Its purpose is two-fold: to serve as a
vehicle for Artificial Intelligence development and as a recreational
competition among software authors.

The original version runs under MS-DOS, but there are ports to many other
platforms. This is the Amiga version. For a more complete introduction,
refer to the @{"original announcement" link "RARS060.ANN/main" 0}. New features of the original version
can be found @{"here" link "whatnew.doc/main" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Internet" "RARS on the Internet"

     @{u}RARS on the Internet@{uu}

There is a @{i}mailing list @{ui}that contains information about new versions, ports
to other platforms, upcoming races and lots of other stuff. To subscribe to
the list, send a message to "listserv@netcom.com" with the line "subscribe
rars-list" in the body of the message. To unsubscribe, send a message to
the same address with the line "unsubscribe rars-list" in the body. The
mailing list is maintained by Rex Sheasby <rshea@netcom.com>.

Furthermore, there's an @{i}FTP site @{ui}which contains tracks, drivers and the
latest version of RARS. The site is called "ftp.best.com" and the RARS
directory is "/pub/ijs/rars". New uploads should be placed in
"/pub/ijs/uploads". Please note that the "/pub" directory itself contains
more than 1000 entries, so be careful when doing a "dir" there! When you
upload a file, please also upload an accompanying ".txt" file (so
exe050.zip should be accompanied by exe050.txt). This file should contain a
short description of the file in question. If you have uploaded something
in the past and want it to be deleted, you should e-mail Jivko Koltchev
<jivko@magdanoz.mcafee.com>, He is the FTP site maintainer.

For all @{i}World Wide Web @{ui}users, there are three different locations where you
can find more information about RARS:

     http://www.cs.bham.ac.uk/~bsr/rars.html
     http://www.mal.com/~dgymer/rars/
     http://www.cris.com/~Nims/mi/mi_rars.html

@{i}Please note that I try to keep this information up to date. If you're not
sure about the validity of some of the addresses, please ask on the mailing
list.@{ui}
@endnode

@node "SystemRequirements" "System requirements"

     @{u}System requirements@{uu}

The Amiga version of RARS needs at least AmigaOS 3.0 (V39) to run. An
accelerated Amiga, possibly with mathematic coprocessor, is needed if you
want to run RARS in real-time. The memory requirements are quite modest. An
Amiga with 512 KB should be enough.

For the layout of the GUI, a small shared library called EAGUI is used.
This library, as well as the header and linker files you need are included
in this archive. However, if you want to know more about EAGUI, you can get
the full archive on Aminet (dev/gui/EAGUI30.lha).

@{i}Please note:@{ui}

This archive only includes a version for an 68030 with 68882. If you have a
different machine, you can either @{"recompile the sources" link "RebuildingTheSources" 0} yourself, or
contact the @{"author" link "AboutTheAuthor" 0} for a version that will run on your computer.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

     @{u}Installation@{uu}

Since you're reading this, you've obviously unpacked the archive. Just put
all files in one directory. You might want to copy the EAGUI.library to
your LIBS: directory, although that is not strictly necessary since
libraries can also be found if they are in the current directory.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

     @{u}Usage@{uu}

Running RARS is as simple as starting it from a shell:

     > RARS_Amiga

This allows you to set all options with a nice GUI. From a list of
available drivers, you can select any number of drivers and change their
order. Below the driver selection lists, you can select a track. All files
that match the "#?.trk" pattern are listed here. To the right of that list
are some track and race options (track surface, number of laps, etc.).
Below these are a number of switches that influence the simulation. Almost
at the bottom of the window, there's a button that allows you to select a
screenmode for the simulation.

All options are saved in an environment variable called RARSOPTS. If you
click on "Save" this environment variable is also stored in ENVARC:.

There is another environment variable, RARSWINDOW, that is automatically
saved. It contains the last-used window dimensions. That way, the window
comes up exactly the same way you left it last time.

When starting RARS, the first thing that is read, is the environment
variable. After that, the command line options are parsed (more on those
below) followed by the settings that the user changes with the GUI.

When selecting a screenmode, always keep in mind that the original MS-DOS
version was meant to run on a 640 x 480, 16 color EGA/VGA screen. Using
virtual screens is possible, and if you use autoscrolling, you can just
move around on the screen with your mouse.

Furthermore, the following option template can be used to specify one or
more options:

     TRACK,DRIVERS/M,CARS/N,PRACTICELAPS/N,LAPS/N,RACES/N,SURFACETYPE/N,
     KEEPORDER/S,NOREALTIME/S,NODISPLAY/S,NORANDOMSEED/N,NORANDOM/S,
     NOKEYBOARD/S,HELP/S,NOGUI/S,SCREENDEPTH/N,SCREENWIDTH/N,
     SCREENHEIGHT/N,SCREENMODEID/N,SCREENOVERSCANTYPE/N,
     SCREENNOAUTOSCROLL/S

     @{i}TRACK @{ui}. . . . . The name of the track file you want to use
                     for this run.

     @{i}DRIVERS @{ui}. . . . You can provide a list of names of drivers that
                     should race on this track. The number of cars is
                     automatically adjusted so that only these drivers
                     will run.

     @{i}CARS.@{ui} . . . . . The number of cars you want to use for this race.
                     There is a maximum, which is hardcoded in the source.
                     What cars are used is also hardcoded.

     @{i}PRACTICELAPS.@{ui} . The number of practice laps before the race.

     @{i}LAPS.@{ui} . . . . . The number of laps in the race.

     @{i}RACES @{ui}. . . . . The number of races you want to do on this track.

     @{i}SURFACETYPE @{ui}. . The type of surface for this track.

     @{i}KEEPORDER @{ui}. . . Keep the same starting order. Using this option will
                     give you the starting order that was specified in the
                     source or, if you've specified the names of the
                     drivers, that order. Otherwise, a random starting
                     order will be generated for every race.

     @{i}NOREALTIME.@{ui} . . A switch which determines if the race should be run
                     in real-time or simply as fast as possible. If the
                     race is really run real-time also depends on the
                     speed of your computer and the number of cars.

     @{i}NODISPLAY @{ui}. . . Don't display the race, only run the simulation as
                     fast as possible. This option automatically selects
                     NOREALTIME.

     @{i}NORANDOMSEED.@{ui} . Don't change the random seed. If you specify this
                     option, the number indicates which seed to use. This
                     should allow you to reproduce races.

     @{i}HELP.@{ui} . . . . . Show command line help for RARS. This is mainly  
                     included for compatibility with the original version
                     since on the Amiga, reading this guide is far more
                     flexible.

     @{i}NOGUI @{ui}. . . . . Don't use the GUI at startup. This allows you
                     to skip the GUI when you use RARS in batch files.

     @{i}SCREENDEPTH @{ui}. . The depth of the screen to use.

     @{i}SCREENWIDTH @{ui}. . The width in pixels of the screen to use.

     @{i}SCREENHEIGHT.@{ui} . The height in pixels of the screen to use.

     @{i}SCREENMODEID.@{ui} . The screen mode ID of the screen to use.
                     If you have access to compiler headers, you can get
                     a list of mode IDs from the <graphics/modeid.h> file.
                     It is much more comfortable however to use the GUI
                     to select the screenmode.

     @{i}SCREENOVERSCANTYPE @{ui} The overscan type of the screen.
                     Again, if you have access to compiler headers, you
                     can fill this out by hand. Otherwise, please use
                     the GUI.

     @{i}SCREENNOAUTOSCROLL @{ui} Switch that allows you to turn off
                     autoscrolling of the screen to use.

This is the standard Amiga command template, so most of you will be
familiar with it. For the others, here are a few examples:

     > @{b}RARS_Amiga Interlagos.trk CARS 5 LAPS 15 @{ub}

     Gives you a 5 car 15 lap race around the Interlagos circuit, in
     real-time if your computer is fast enough.

     > @{b}RARS_Amiga Zandvoort.trk CARS=8 LAPS=10 NOREALTIME @{ub}

     This time you get an 8 car 15 lap race around the Zandvoort circuit.
     The race will be run as fast as possible.

     > @{b}RARS_Amiga LAPS 2 CARS 12 TRACK RARS.trk @{ub}

     A two lap race on the neat looking RARS track in which 12 cars will
     compete.

     > @{b}RARS_Amiga TRACK=Indy500 LAPS=200 RACES=1 DRIVERS Arelys Ramdu2 @{ub}

     Starts the full distance Indianapolis 500 race. The drivers Arelys
     and Ramdu2 will compete in this race.

     > @{b}RARS_Amiga NODISPLAY @{ub}

     Starts a race without displaying anything on screen.

When RARS is running with a display, it will wait for a keypress before
starting a practice session or race. While the cars are driving around the
circuit, you can abort the race by pressing ESC. The instrument panel is
activated with the 2 and 8 keys, which go down and up the list
respectively. The P key pauses the game, any key resumes afterwards. The F
and S keys turn on fast (as fast as possible) and slow (real-time) mode
respectively. At the end of the race, RARS waits for you to press a key
before closing down.

If you want to learn more about the simulation itself, take a look at the
@{"original documentation" link "RARS050.DOC/main" 0}. Here you'll also find what the defaults for the
above options are.
@endnode

@node "CreatingTracks" "Creating your own tracks"

     @{u}Creating your own tracks@{uu}

In the past, creating a track was a very difficult task. This was mainly
caused by the fact that turns had to be described by their outer rail. Now
you can create tracks by simply describing the centerline of the track.
These new track files can be recognized by a negative number of track
segments. Let's look at a simple oval:

     -4                  track segments
     1000 700            size of track
     80                  width of track

     200 100             outer rail starting point
     200 650             scoreboard upper left
     500 650             leaderboard upper left
     750 650             instrument panel upper left
     200 250             track length message
     0.5                 fraction of 1st segment prior to finish line

     0 600               straight, 600 ft long
     150 180             first corner, 180 degrees, 150 ft radius
     0 600               straight, 600 ft long
     150 180             second corner, 180 degrees, 150 ft radius

The second example is a bit more complicated. Take a look:

     -9                  track segments
     1000 800            size of track
     150                 width of track

     200 100             outer rail starting point
     200 750             scoreboard upper left
     500 775             leaderboard upper left
     800 775             instrument panel upper left
     200 25              track length message
     0.5                 fraction of 1st segment prior to finish line

     0 600               straight, 600 ft long
     100 90              90 degree left turn, 100 ft radius
     0 200               200 ft long straight
     100 90              90 degree left turn, 100 ft radius
     0 100               100 ft long straight
     100 90              90 degree left turn, 100 ft radius
     -100 90             90 degree right turn, 100 ft radius
     0 300               300 ft long straight
     100 180             180 degree left turn, 100 ft radius

These two tracks can be found under the names "Test 1.trk" and "Test
2.trk". Any text after the numbers on each line is ignored, so you can
safely add comments to the track files. More information about the track
file format can be found in (for example) "@{"Trackfile.trk" link "Trackfile.trk/main" 0}".
@endnode

@node "RebuildingTheSources" "Rebuilding the sources"

     @{u}Rebuilding the sources@{uu}

If you want to rebuild the sources yourself, you need the SAS/C compiler
version 6.55. A makefile ("smakefile") has been provided.

This makefile contains the following symbolic targets that you can use to
manage the project:

 @{i}all @{ui}. . . . . Compiles all the sources and links them. If everything went
               well, you'll get an executable called RARS_Amiga in the
               same directory. If you want to recompile for a different
               CPU or an FPU, you can just run SCOpts to change the
               options and then recompile everything.

 @{i}cleanup @{ui}. . . Removes all object files from the project directory. You
               can use this option to clean up the project after it's been
               built or you can use it to force a complete new compilation
               after you've changed the compiler options. I have not
               included the SCOPTIONS file in the dependency list of the
               makefile on purpose, so that you can selectively recompile
               modules after you've changed the options. You can use this
               to turn on debugging for certain modules (for example your
               own driver).

 @{i}delete.@{ui} . . . Does a cleanup and deletes the executable too. Only the
               sources are kept.

 @{i}release @{ui}. . . Builds everything and creates a distribution archive on the
               RAM disk. This is mainly included for releasing new
               versions, but you can also use it to send someone the
               complete package after you've modified it.

Make sure to modify the makefile whenever you add a driver (just add it to
the CARSRCS= and CAROBJS= lines at the top). The makefile is designed to
work with the SCOPTIONS file that is supplied in the archive. The imporant
thing is that you leave on the LINK option.
@endnode

@node "AboutTheAuthor" "About the author"

     @{u}About the author@{uu}

I ported RARS to the Amiga because of two reasons. For one, I have done
some genetic algorithm programming for my study myself and I am hoping to
write a genetically designed driver in the future. The other reason was the
fun aspect of it, I just like racing games.

I developed and tested this program on an:

     Amiga 3000T with 2 MB Chip RAM and 12 MB Fast RAM
     Quantum LPS 120 MB SCSI harddisk
     Quantum Maverick 540 MB SCSI harddisk
     Toshiba XM5201B/S SCSI CD-ROM
     AmigaOS 3.1

For comments, suggestions or questions, you can reach me at the following
address:

     Marcel Offermans

     e-mail : M.F.Offermans@WbMT.TUDelft.NL
     fidonet: 2:281/614.1
@endnode

@node "ReleaseHistory" "Release history"

     @{u}Release history@{uu}

Release 1 (21.3.95)

Based on the 0.39 sources. This is very much a straight port. There's room
for a lot of further enhancements, both in this port and in the original
version. However, this release is enough to get everybody going, and it is
in time for the first competition!

Release 2 (27.3.95)

Based on the 0.45 sources. It is still a fairly straight port, but it has
more features, because it is based on a newer revision of the sources.
Furthermore, the track drawing and filling have been improved, as well as
the text output to the graphical screen.

Release 3 (25.5.95)

Based on the 0.60 sources. Again, a fairly straight port of an ever growing
original version. This release includes a complete tutorial on how to write
a driver. Furthermore, this release features a new track loader, which
allows tracks to be created more easily. The most noticable change however
is the inclusion of a new GUI that allows you to set all the options more
easily.
@endnode

@node "KnownBugs" "Known bugs"

     @{u}Known bugs@{uu}

None. The bug in the SAS/C 6.55 compiler that was troubling the last
version of RARS has disappeared because of a change in RARS.

If you've found a bug, please report it to me. Try to give a detailed bug
report, not something like `RARS crashes on my machine' but describe all
relevant details of your system and how to reproduce the bug. The moral: if
I can't reproduce it here, I probably can't find or fix it either.
@endnode

